Unlike standard linear attention, where the decay is often a fixed scalar or a simple data-independent curve, RWKV-7 employs Vector-Valued In-Context Learning Rates. The decay rate is calculated per-channel and per-token based on the input xt‚Äã. This allows the model to perform complex "forgetting" operations. If the model encounters a boundary between two unrelated documents in the corpus, it can dynamically drive the decay rates for specific channels toward zero, effectively resetting those parts of the state and preventing information contamination.  

2.2.2 Decoupled Keys and Associative Recall

A critical innovation in RWKV-7 is the decoupling of the keys used for reading from the state and the keys used for writing to the state. In standard linear attention (like RetNet or RWKV-4), the same key vector kt‚Äã determines both where information is stored and how it interferes with previous information. This coupling limits the model's ability to handle the "associative recall" task‚Äîretrieving a specific value vi‚Äã given a query q that matches a key ki‚Äã seen thousands of steps ago.  

By decoupling these mechanisms, RWKV-7 solves the "saturation" problem. It can selectively overwrite outdated information while protecting salient memories. This capability is analogous to a "Write Enable" line in a memory cell, controlled by the semantic content of the stream. This property is vital for a Knowledge Engine: as it reads a textbook, it must update its internal definition of a variable as the context evolves, without losing the broader context of the chapter.
2.2.3 Meta-In-Context Learning

The architecture is described as a "meta-in-context learner". The state update rule can be viewed theoretically as a single step of gradient descent on a "hidden" weight matrix (the state S) utilizing a specialized loss function derived from the current token prediction. As the model processes the context, it effectively "trains" itself to recognize the specific linguistic and semantic patterns of the current document. This "Test-Time Training" is not an iterative loop but an intrinsic property of the forward pass recurrence. This aligns perfectly with our goal of minimizing Power/Token‚Äîwe achieve adaptation without the cost of backpropagation or iterative optimization.  

2.3 Mamba-3: The MIMO Evolution of State Space Models

Competing closely with RWKV-7 is Mamba-3, detailed in submissions around late 2025. Mamba-3 evolves the Structured State Space (S4) lineage, addressing the primary weakness of its predecessors: hardware efficiency on GPUs.  

2.3.1 The MIMO Formulation

Previous linear models (including Mamba-1 and Mamba-2) relied on a Single-Input Single-Output (SISO) formulation for their recurrent scan. While mathematically elegant, SISO operations are notoriously difficult to parallelize on modern GPUs, which are designed for massive matrix multiplications (Tensor Cores). The arithmetic intensity (ratio of compute to memory access) of a SISO scan is low; the processor spends more time moving the small state S from memory than computing updates.

Mamba-3 introduces a Multi-Input Multi-Output (MIMO) formulation. It aggregates inputs into blocks, allowing the recurrence to process chunks of the state vector in parallel.
 

