In the MIMO formulation, the matrices A, B, and C, and the state h are structured to allow block-diagonal or block-circulant operations. This structure maps efficiently to matrix multiplication units, significantly increasing the FLOP utilization of the hardware.
2.3.2 Hardware-Aware Efficiency and the Pareto Frontier

The Mamba-3 architecture is explicitly designed with an "inference-first" perspective. By increasing the state size dstate‚Äã (which proxies for the "memory capacity" of the sequence) without a linear increase in decoding latency (thanks to MIMO parallelism), Mamba-3 pushes the Pareto frontier of performance versus inference budget. The authors demonstrate that Mamba-3 allows for richer state tracking capabilities‚Äîessential for maintaining coherence over long documents‚Äîwithout the latency penalty associated with larger states in SISO models.  

For the Knowledge Engine, Mamba-3 offers a specific advantage in Hybrid Architectures. Research indicates that hybrid models (e.g., predominantly Mamba layers with 2-4 attention layers) can outperform pure linear models in needle-in-a-haystack retrieval tasks. However, this introduces the complexity of managing a KV cache, however small, which violates our strictest interpretation of the "Antirez" minimalism.  

